article.headline: Kansas State on an 11-game win streak
article.linkText: Kansas State beats Kansas for fifth straight time
article.story:
MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Nicole Ohlde nearly had the perfect
exclamation point to Kansas State's 79-50 victory over Kansas on
Saturday. It was a fast-break dunk that just missed.

Ohlde called it "pretty weak," but the rest of her team's
performance was pretty strong.

Ohlde had 20 points and nine rebounds, helping Kansas
State (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) dominate early to win its 11th straight and fifth straight
over its in-state rivals.

"It's always difficult to play her," Kansas forward Crystal
Kemp said of Ohlde. "She's got great foot work and she is tall."

The Wildcats (13-2, 4-0 Big 12) shot 66 percent in the first
half and held the Jayhawks to 32 percent for the game. During their
winning streak, they have won by an average of 31.8 points.

"We're starting to click well right now," Ohlde said. "And
I'm getting some open looks."

She's wasn't the only one getting shots. Megan Mahoney had 15
points, seven assists and seven rebounds. Kendra Wecker added 11
and Twiggy McIntyre had 10.

"Teams always have to watch out for Nicole, Kendra and Laurie
(Koehn) so that gave Twiggy and I open looks," Mahoney said.

The Wildcats could barely miss early.

They made seven of their first eight shots, including
back-to-back 3-pointers by Mahoney, to take a 19-6 lead with 15:02
left. Mahoney scored 11 points in the first five minutes of the
game.

Blair Waltz hit a three with 13:14 left to cut the deficit to
eight, but Kansas State struck again.

A 12-1 run made the lead 37-18 with 8:19 left and the Jayhawks,
who shot just 31.6 percent from the floor, never fully recovered.

"When they started hitting from outside that really hurt us,"
Kansas coach Marian Washington said. "Down the stretch, we did a
better job certainly then we started."

Kansas State led 52-26 at the break, but scored just 27 in the
second half.

Aquanita Burras led Kansas (8-7, 1-3) with 17, Blair Waltz
scored 14 and Crystal Kemp had 13.

"The last few minutes were good," Burras said. "We'll take
that as a positive."

Tamara Ransburg, Larisha Graves and Kandis Bonner sat out the
game for Kansas because they were serving a one-game NCAA
suspension for fighting with Missouri players Jan. 10. Ransburg and
Graves were starters.
